Backport of upstream axios PR #10858 (merge caa00a9, released as v1.16.1) to
axios v1.8.3, addressing AIKIDO-2026-10823 (CWE-319: HTTPS request data sent
in cleartext to HTTP proxy).

Root cause in v1.8.3: setProxy() unconditionally rewrites options.hostname /
options.port / options.path / options.protocol to point at the proxy and
switches the request into forward-proxy mode for every proxied request,
regardless of whether the origin is http:// or https://. When the caller
asked for https://origin/... axios still sent the full absolute URL, request
headers, and body to the proxy in cleartext (or to the proxy's TLS session
which terminates at the proxy, not the origin). Any proxy on the path -
including one injected via HTTPS_PROXY env var - saw and could tamper with
the whole request.

Fix (semantic backport of the v1.16.1 change) - implemented WITHOUT adding a
runtime dependency, since the internal npm build hook for axios@1.8.3 uses
`mode: universal` / `alias: true` and does NOT run `npm install`, so any new
`dependencies` entry in package.json cannot be resolved at build time.
Instead of pulling `https-proxy-agent`, this patch inlines a minimal CONNECT
tunnel implementation on top of Node's built-in `net`, `tls`, `http`, `https`,
`url` modules:

  * A local `HttpsTunnelAgent` class extends `https.Agent` and overrides
    `createConnection(options, callback)`. It opens a plain `net.connect`
    (or `tls.connect` when the proxy scheme is https:) to the configured
    proxy host:port, writes an HTTP CONNECT request naming the true origin
    host:port (with an optional Basic Proxy-Authorization line built from
    proxy.auth only - never from the target request's Authorization header),
    buffers the proxy response until the CRLFCRLF terminator, and on
    HTTP/1.x 200 upgrades the socket via `tls.connect({ socket, servername:
    <origin host>, ... })` so the ClientHello, HTTP request, and body all
    travel end-to-end encrypted to the origin. Non-200 responses, socket
    errors, and premature close are surfaced as an AxiosError through the
    createConnection callback.
  * A module-level `Map` caches tunnel agents by proxy URL + target host:port
    + proxy-auth, so repeat requests through the same proxy reuse a single
    agent (and its socket pool). The keyspace is bounded by the set of
    distinct proxy configs the process uses.
  * When the target scheme is HTTPS, setProxy() now installs the tunneling
    agent on both `options.agent` (for the `config.maxRedirects === 0` path
    that goes straight to https.request) and `options.agents.https` (for the
    follow-redirects path, which ignores `options.agent` when `options.agents`
    is present). It leaves `options.hostname`, `options.port`, `options.path`,
    and `options.protocol` pointing at the true origin so TLS SNI and
    certificate verification apply to the origin, not the proxy. User TLS
    options from `config.httpsAgent` (custom CA, rejectUnauthorized, client
    cert) are forwarded into the tunnel agent so pinning / verification
    behavior is preserved.
  * When the target scheme is HTTP, keep v1.8.3's existing forward-proxy
    behavior verbatim: stamp Proxy-Authorization onto request headers and
    rewrite hostname/port/path/protocol to point at the proxy. Plaintext HTTP
    is already inspectable on the wire so this branch is unchanged.
  * The redirect closure forwards `config.httpsAgent` through recursive
    setProxy() calls and, before recomputing proxy state, strips any
    tunneling agent we installed on the previous hop (matched by the
    `kAxiosInstalledTunnel` Symbol so a user-supplied agent that happens to
    be a proxy agent is left alone). This prevents a stale HTTPS-target
    CONNECT agent from leaking into a subsequent HTTP-target hop or a
    no-proxy hop.
  * The httpAdapter call site now passes isRedirect=false and
    config.httpsAgent to setProxy(), and no longer clobbers a tunneling
    agent installed by setProxy() when it later assigns options.agent based
    on the target protocol.

Deltas from the upstream fix (adjustments made for v1.8.3):
  * v1.8.3 lacks the readProxyField() prototype-pollution-safe accessor
    (added post-1.8.3). We use direct proxy.hostname / proxy.host /
    proxy.port / proxy.protocol reads, matching v1.8.3's existing setProxy
    style.
  * v1.8.3's proxy.auth handling is inlined at the top of the branch. We
    compute a proxyAuth string once and thread it through both the HTTPS
    (tunnel agent) and HTTP (Proxy-Authorization header) branches.
  * v1.8.3 lacks the Object-form auth AxiosError('Invalid proxy
    authorization') branch. We preserve v1.8.3's forgiving behavior:
    if proxy.auth is an object with username/password, coalesce into a
    string; otherwise leave as-is.
  * v1.8.3 lacks the user-supplied Host-header preservation (added post-
    1.8.3). We keep v1.8.3's simple options.headers.host = hostname:port
    on the HTTP-target branch only, matching upstream's decision to skip
    the Host header on the CONNECT-tunneled HTTPS branch (the Host header
    now travels inside TLS to the origin).
  * README.md and THREATMODEL.md prose updates from the fix are
    documentation-only and are not included (v1.8.3's README section text
    diverges significantly and THREATMODEL.md doesn't exist in v1.8.3;
    neither affects security behavior).
  * The upstream regression tests live at tests/unit/adapters/http.test.js
    (vitest); v1.8.3 uses mocha at test/unit/adapters/http.js with a very
    different scaffold. Test-file rebase is out of scope for the security
    fix; verification is expected via manual regression against an HTTP
    proxy (issue #6320 reproducer).
  * package.json is intentionally NOT modified. The upstream fix adds
    `https-proxy-agent` as a runtime dep; we implement the CONNECT tunnel
    in-tree using Node built-ins because the axios@1.8.3 hook does not run
    `npm install` and cannot resolve a newly introduced dep.

